body:
This code:
```
interface ifc #(parameter int width)(logic [width-1:0] b);
    logic [width-1:0] a;
    typedef logic[$bits(type(a))-1:0] type_t;
    always_comb a = type_t'(b);
endinterface

module tb();
    logic [15:0] x;
    ifc #(.width(16)) x_ifc(x);
    logic [7:0] y;
    ifc #(.width(8)) y_ifc(y);
endmodule
```
generates a warning on the second instance:
```
%Warning-WIDTHTRUNC: issue.sv:4:19: Operator ASSIGN expects 8 bits on the Assign RHS, but Assign RHS's CASTWRAP generates 16 bits.
                                  : ... note: In instance 'tb'
    4 |     always_comb a = type_t'(b);
      |                   ^
                     ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/WIDTHTRUNC?v=5.045
                     ... Use "/* verilator lint_off WIDTHTRUNC */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
```
Seemingly by having an internally incorrect notion of the width which should be harmless in this example but could potentially lead to real truncations. This:
```
interface ifc #(parameter int width)(logic [width-1:0] b);
    logic [width-1:0] a;
    typedef logic[$bits(type(a))-1:0] type_t;
    always_comb a = type_t'(b);
endinterface

module tb();
    logic [15:0] x = 16'hFFFF;
    ifc #(.width(16)) x_ifc(x);
    initial begin
        $display(x_ifc.a);
    end
endmodule
```
produces the expected `65535`. However, reintroducing the other smaller instance before it:
```
interface ifc #(parameter int width)(logic [width-1:0] b);
    logic [width-1:0] a;
    typedef logic[$bits(type(a))-1:0] type_t;
    always_comb a = type_t'(b);
endinterface

module tb();
    logic [7:0] y;
    ifc #(.width(8)) y_ifc(y);
    logic [15:0] x = 16'hFFFF;
    ifc #(.width(16)) x_ifc(x);
    initial begin
        $display(x_ifc.a);
    end
endmodule
```

and building with `-Wno-WIDTHEXPAND` results in `255`.

From bisecting, this seems to have been introduced with #6732

